Part I - Prosper Loan Data¶

by Kose Bilali Salim¶

Introduction¶

The Prosper Loan dataset contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others. I will explore about 10-15 variables both categorical variables

    ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, categories = ordinal_var[var])
    df_loans[var] = df_loans[var].astype(ordered_var)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan in the dataset. In the selected variables, most are numberic. They are Term, BorrowerRate, ListingCategory (numeric), StatedMonthlyIncome, TotalProsperLoans,ListingCategory (numeric), Recommendations, Investors. The selected variables LoanStatus, EmploymentStatus categorical-nominal

  • ListingCategory: 0 - Not Available, 1 - Debt Consolidation, 2 - Home Improvement, 3 - Business, 4 - Personal Loan, 5 - Student Use, 6 - Auto, 7- Other, 8 - Baby&Adoption, 9 - Boat, 10 - Cosmetic Procedure, 11 - Engagement Ring, 12 - Green Loans, 13 - Household Expenses, 14 - Large Purchases, 15 - Medical/Dental, 16 - Motorcycle, 17 - RV, 18 - Taxes, 19 - Vacation, 20 - Wedding Loans

  • ProsperRating (numeric): 0 - N/A, 1 - HR, 2 - E, 3 - D, 4 - C, 5 - B, 6 - A, 7 - AA.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested in finding out how employment status and ProperRating affect loan amount given and loan default

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that employment status, ProperRating, and StatedMonthlyIncome will have effect on the loan default/completion, and loan amount given. The higer the stated monthly income,the higher the loan being given. And the better the properRating, the more likely a borrower will not default.

base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]

# Helper functions

#function to setup chart title,labels, size, and xticks rotation
def fig_polish(title, xlabel, ylabel, size=(8,5), xticks=90):
    plt.figure(figsize=size)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.xticks(rotation = xticks);

Since there's a left skew of the data in the distribution, let's plot the distribution on a log scale instead

In [93]:
# ploting on a log scale
log_binsize = 0.025
bins = 10 ** np.arange(2.4, np.log10(df_loans['StatedMonthlyIncome'].max())+log_binsize, log_binsize)
fig_polish('Count of Stated Monthly Income', 'Stated Monthly Income','Count') # call the custom polish function
plt.hist(data = df_loans, x = 'StatedMonthlyIncome', bins = bins)
plt.xscale('log') # log scale
plt.xticks([250,1e3, 5e3, 10e3, 20e3, 50e3, 100e3], [250, '1k', '5k', '10k', '20k', '50k','100k'])
plt.show()

Summary observations from StatedMonthlyIncome¶

  • By taking the bins as a logarthmic value ie log scale, we still get a left skew, but this time with a stated monthly value of 5000 ie 5K.
  • This distributions shows some kind of normal distributions- an Increase in monthly income does not increase the loan borrowing

Summary observations from Loan Status¶

  • We can observe that most of the loans are the Current ones
  • Completed loans falls the second with a count of about 20000.
  • Other loans status falls betwee 15 days and 60 days delays, while those past 120 days delays are the least occurance.
  • Since we are interested in the loan defaulted and loan completed, we will use pandas filtering to only have this two values in the next chart

Our interest is only the loan defaulted and loan completed, so we use pandas filtering to only have this two values' data

In [104]:

# helper function for the check the distribution of employment status and loan status against LoanOriginalAmount and StatedMonthlyIncome
def employment_loan_status(hue, axis, title):
    df_loans_sample = df_loans.head(500); # use sample 500 data to reduce execution speed and performance
    sb.pointplot(data = df_loans_sample, x = 'LoanOriginalAmount', y = 'StatedMonthlyIncome', hue = hue,
                 palette = 'Blues', linestyles = '', dodge = 0.4, ax = ax[axis])
    ax[axis].set_title(title)
    ax[axis].set_xlabel('Linear scale of LoanOriginalAmount ($)')
    ax[axis].set_ylabel('StatedMonthlyIncome ($)')
    ax[axis].set_xscale('linear')
